passages.text: Equity Research August 28, 2025

We update our model for following an interview with the deputy CEO and Q1 results. While Q1 results were satisfactory, the trend in new business and growing CSM pool is probably not meeting the bullish scenario. Whilst we appreciate that Lifenet has achieved technological advances such as same- day insurance payouts in some cases, we need to see this increasing the value of new business of individual insurance. Retain Hold at PEV of 1.2x.

Deputy CEO Meeting: We conducted an IR meeting with Mr. Takeshi Kawasaki, deputy president and CFO. The key points are 1) The company is preparing to add another bank for the provision of group credit insurance, 2) The company estimates that online insurance accounts for around \(1 - 2\%\) of which Lifenet has \(30 - 40\%\) market share vs around \(10\%\) in car insurance, so there is room to grow, 3) Currently there is enough capital without immediate fundraising. Equity issuance will depend on future big projects and there is no point in just increasing equity as it will be a hindrance to ROE, 4) From the competitive market, Lifenet is not trying to be the cheapest provider, but it wants to be the best at UI and UX.

Our View Following the Meeting: Three activist funds have declared stakes in the company, and will have benefited from the recent share- price increase. However, if growth in individual insurance and adding another bank to provide mortgage insurance do not occur quickly enough, management may come under pressure. The company has a mid- term target of \(200 - 240bn\) in comprehensive equity and a \(3,000\) share price for FY28 (i.e., three years' time). We believe that the share price target in particular will probably have to be revised up to meet current investor expectations.

Thoughts on Profitability: By dividing insurance operating profits (Lifenet calls this insurance service results) by annualized premium (average of beginning and end quarters), we can estimate the gross profit ratio. For Q1, individual insurance was \(32.7\%\) (FY3/25 \(30.6\%\) ) and group insurance \(37.5\%\) (FY3/25 \(28.7\%\) ). As can be seen, normally individual insurance has higher gross profit ratio but in Q1 group insurance had higher profitability, this was probably based on the timing of the contract payments.

Our Earnings Estimates: We have revenue of \(32.9bn\) for FY3/26E (guidance \(33.0bn\) ,cons \(33.5bn\) and EBT of \(10.7bn\) (cons \(10.6bn\) ) and net profit of \(7.5bn\) (guidance \(6.9bn\) ,cons \(7.2bn\) ).

Valuation/Risks: We use Price to Comprehensive Equity (CE, similar to EEV - European Embedded Value) at 1.05x. (please refer to the exhibit below or ask us for the model). The risks are that the value of new business is below investor expectations, which could bring down the valuation, and not forming further banking mortgage credit insurance pipelines.

- Unique business model as an independent online life insurer.- Recent change in management may be a catalyst. The previous president was Mr. Mori, who established the alliance with KDDI. New president is Mr. Junpei Yokozawa. He was previously at NTT Data and headed the systems development and data science divisions.- Use of internet for life insurance has many benefits such as being fairly priced. The company is moving to more flexible insurance products such as group credit insurance.- There is competition from other online life insurance companies such as Rakuten Life, Orix Life, Sony Life (although Sony operates more of a life planner model).
Risk/Reward - 12 Month View

- Gradual increase in market share for Lifenet.- Status quo of non-listed life insurers such as Nippon Life and Sony Life.- Management stance will be similar to the previous.- Price to Comprehensive Equity (CE, similar to EEV - European Embedded Value) at 1.05x

- Lifenet has been successful in getting new alliances such as KDDI, SM Card, Money Forward. We would view further alliances with other subscription companies such as utilities favourably.- Gradual increase in market share for Lifenet.- Status quo from non-listed life insurers such as Nippon Life and Sony Life.- Management stance will be similar to the previous.
- Fierce competition from other online life insurers such as Orix, Rakuten.- Established large traditional entities look to move into online insurance space.- Price to Comprehensive Equity to shrink

- Environment: As an online life insurer, the application is done by PCs or smartphones thereby cutting many unwanted paper applications that traditional life insurers use. In addition, as an internet life insurer, Lifenet cuts down on many unnecessary branch networks.- Social: In Nov 2015, Lifenet became the first life insurer in Japan to allow same-sex partners to receive life payouts, therefore supporting LGBI + causes.- Governance: The company has seven board members of which five are outside and four are independent. The non-independent director is from KDDI, who is a large shareholder. The other large shareholders include Seven Financial Service and Sumitomo Mitsui Card.
- Quarterly earnings.- The new president coming up with new interesting ideas, products or alliances.- Change in Base Rates and equity value forecasts affecting yields.

Lifenet InsuranceLifenet is an online insurance company founded in 2006 and began its operations in 2008. It was the first company in Japan to offer insurance through mobile phones. Its business partners includes au Jibun bank and SMBC. As an independent new company, Lifenet is trying to establish itself as a new generation life insurance company amongst the traditional insurers.

We value Lifenet on Price/Comprehensive Equity multiples based on its growth profile. Downside risks to our thesis are 1) competition from other online insurance companies such as Rakuten 2) uneconomic positioning of insurance assets 3) the alliances not concluding as expected. Upside risks are 1) rapid take up of Lifenet products 2) new CEO succeeding in strategy.

Buy - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of \(15\%\) or more within a 12- month period.

Hold - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of plus \(15\%\) or minus \(10\%\) within a 12- month period. Underperform - Describes securities that we expect to provide a total return (price appreciation plus yield) of minus \(10\%\) or less within a 12- month period. The expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) for Buy rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) is \(20\%\) or more within a 12- month period as these companies are typically more volatile than the overall stock market. For Hold rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) , the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is plus or minus \(20\%\) within a 12- month period. For Underperform rated securities with an average security price consistently below \(10\) , the expected total return (price appreciation plus yield) is minus \(20\%\) or less within a 12- month period.

Jefferies Franchise PicksJefferies Franchise Picks include stock selections from among the best stock ideas from our equity analysts over a 12 month period. Stock selection is based on fundamental analysis and may take into account other factors such as analyst conviction, differentiated analysis, a favorable risk/reward ratio and investment themes that Jefferies analysts are recommending. Jefferies Franchise Picks will include only Buy rated stocks and the number can vary depending on analyst recommendations for inclusion. Stocks will be added as new opportunities arise and removed when the reason for inclusion changes, the stock has met its desired return, if it is no longer rated Buy and/or if it triggers a stop loss. Stocks having 120 day volatility in the bottom quartile of S&P stocks will continue to have a 15% stop loss, and the remainder will have a 20% stop.
